why probes?
By default, kubernetes only checks if main process is running or not. it does not check if internal functionality is working as expected or not.

types:
1) Liveness probe:
2) Readiness probe:
3) Startup probe:

Different Types of Probing mechanism:
1) Exec
 this mechanism is used to execute a command to check if pod is healthy or not.

 Pod will be considered healthy if command executes with status 0

 ex:
 exec:
   command:
     - mongo
     - --eval
     - "db.adminCommand('ping')"

2) HTTP

with HTTP, we ask kubernetes to perform a http request to a url ( actuator ).

Healthy if res contains 200-399 status code.

ex: 
httpGet:
  path: /health
  port: 8080

3) TCP

with this, we open a port on container.

Healthy if container accept traffic on given port

Concept: How many times should it retry if command(probing mechanism) should fail 

1) initialDelaySeconds (Default Value = 0sec): how much k8 should wait after container is attached.
  
2) periodSeconds (Default Value = 10sec): how frequently probe should be executed after initial delay

if it fails container is restarted.

3) timeoutSeconds (Default Value = 1sec): Timeout period to mark as failure.

4) failure/successThreshold (Default Value = 3times): how many times kubernetes shoud retry in case of failure.

container will only be restarted if probe fails for this number of times

Main Types:
1) Liveness probe:

livenessProbe is written at container level.

when liveness probe fails K8 keeps Restarting pods until lineness probe success.

Ex: 
livenessProbe:
  exec:
    command:
      - mongo
      - --eval
      - "db.adminCommand('ping')"

2) Readiness Probes:

This Probe identifies when a container can handle external traffic recieved from service.

just like liveness probe we can use readiness probe.

if readiness probe failes k8 remove ip address of pod from endpoints.

ex:
ReadinessProbe:
  exec:
    command:
      - mongo
      - --eval
      - "db.adminCommand('ping')"
 
 3) Startup probe:

Startup probe provides a way to delay above 2 probe until container can handle that.

if Startup probe fails it follows restart policy and kills the container.



Best Practices:

Ideal frequency
Lightweight
Correct Restart Policy
Use only when needed
Keep an eye on Probes Regularly	
